I found that problem some months ago. Didn't really open a issue at the time because I assumed the IL is technically invalid according to the spec (but now reading it again, I don't see anything on it that explicitly says this kind of pattern is invalid). But the interesting part is that it does work fine with the mono JIT. Here's a very simple program that shows the issue:
```cs
using System;
using System.Reflection.Emit;

namespace ILTest
{
    delegate int TestMethod();

    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            DynamicMethod meth = new DynamicMethod("TryMe", typeof(int), null);

            ILGenerator generator = meth.GetILGenerator();

            generator.Emit(OpCodes.Ldc_I4_1);

            Label lbl = generator.DefineLabel();

            generator.MarkLabel(lbl);
            generator.Emit(OpCodes.Brfalse_S, lbl);
            generator.Emit(OpCodes.Ldc_I4_1);
            generator.Emit(OpCodes.Ret);

            int result = ((TestMethod)meth.CreateDelegate(typeof(TestMethod)))();

            Console.WriteLine("Result: " + result);
        }
    }
}
```
On .NET Core it throws:
```
System.InvalidProgramException: The JIT compiler encountered invalid IL code or an internal limitation.
```
On mono it works fine, printing `Result: 1` and exiting.

I recently saw https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/39765 which apparently tries to fix a somewhat similar issue (well, not exactly the same, but it also arose due to a discrepancy between mono and .NET Core JIT), although in this case its the opposite problem (it works on mono but not .NET Core).

Does it make sense to file issues for interesting missing optimizations in JIT?
E.g. so called (Early) Tail Deduplication:
```csharp
void Test1(bool condition)
{
    if (condition)
    {
        Foo1();
    }
    else
    {
        Foo2();
    }
    Foo3();
}
```
Can be converted to:
```csharp
void Test2(bool condition)
{
    if (condition)
    {
        Foo1();
        Foo3();
    }
    else
    {
        Foo2();
        Foo3();
    }
}
```
so it eliminates a jump for cases when `condition` is true (Modern C++ compilers do it: https://godbolt.org/z/vVdsGV). However, in theory, JIT could collect some profile data and re-order calls for the most popular value for `condition`...

There is a bug in File.WriteAllLines wherein it writes an extra newline at the end.
It's easy to reproduce: 

```
[TestMethod]
public void WriteAllLines()
{
            string noEmptyLineAtTheEnd = "Hello" + Environment.NewLine + "World";            

            File.WriteAllText("File1.txt", noEmptyLineAtTheEnd);            
            File.WriteAllLines("File2.txt", File.ReadAllLines("File1.txt"));

            Assert.AreEqual(File.ReadAllText("File1.txt").EndsWith(Environment.NewLine), File.ReadAllText("File2.txt").EndsWith(Environment.NewLine));
            // result:   Assert.AreEqual failed. Expected:<False>. Actual:<True>. 
}
```

A reasonable person could not be faulted for expecting that reading all lines and then writing all lines would produce a copy with the same number of lines, it doesn't.

There's some awful XML out there that uses such a multitude of element names that it's infeasible to map them all out in explicit `XMLElement` attributes. Heck, such XML is usually produced with  dynamically generated names. It's a horrible practice - not to be encouraged, but we should be able to simplify the life of people who need to interoperate with such XML.

It'd be nice if we could do this:

```
class AwfulElement {
  [XmlDynamicElementName]
  string name;
  [XmlText(typeOf(int))]
  int aNumber;
  ...
}
```

Other names for the proposed attribute may be `XmlInteropDynamicElementName` to signify that this is for interop purposes only, or `XmlAwfulDynamicElementName` to make it abundantly clear what it is :/

### Rationale

As it stands, `XmlSerializer` infrastructure does a very poor job of supporting this - it requires quite a bit of semi-efficient code. Imagine you wanted a bunch of such elements in a collection with the following spec (note that currently it requires having an `INamedElement`, but with the support for the proposed attribute there'd be no need for it):

```
partial class AwfulCollection<T> : IXmlSerializable, IEnumerable<T> where T : INamedElement, new();

class AwfulParent {
  public AwfulCollection<AwfulElement> Elements;
}

<?xml>
<AwfulParemt>
  <Awful1\>
  <Awful2\>
</AwfulParent>
```

I'll spare the details, but implementing this generic `AwfulCollection` is a pain. With the support for the proposed attribute, the usual array could be used:

```
class LessAwfulParent {
  public AwfulElement[] Element;
}
```

### Spec

The attribute definition would be rather basic. A `DefaultElementName` property is a fallback if the name the attribute applies to is null. An exception would be thrown on serialization if both the name-attributed field as well as the default name were empty. On deserialization, the `name` is filled in with the name of the element.

```
[System.AttributeUsageAttribute(System.AttributeTargets.Field | System.AttributeTargets.Property, AllowMultiple=false)]
    public partial class XmlDynamicElementNameAttribute: System.Attribute
    {
        public XmlDynamicElementNameAttribute() { }
        public XmlDynamicElementNameAttribute(string defaultElementName) { }
        public string DefaultElementName { get { throw null; } set { } }
        public System.Xml.Schema.XmlSchemaForm Form { get { throw null; } set { } }
        public string Namespace { get { throw null; } set { } }
    }
```

